    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Metro Business Briefing; BUFFALO UNEMPLOYMENT</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Leslie Eaton</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Eaton, Leslie</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Buffalo's Niagara Falls area of New York and Miami, Fla, have highest big-city unemployment rates in country at 4.9 percent (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Buffalo-Niagara Falls area has tied with Miami as having the highest big-city unemployment rate in the country, according to data released yesterday by the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics. The jobless rate in both areas in December was 4.9 percent; the New York City area ranked third at 4.8 percent. It could be worse: in Yuma, Ariz., a small city on the border with Mexico, the unemployment rate is 15.8 percent. Connecticut continued to dominate the list of places with low unemployment. Danbury and the Stamford-Norwalk area registered jobless rates in December of just 1 percent, the lowest of all metropolitan areas; Hartford, at 1.6 percent, was second-lowest among big cities, after San Jose, Calif.</p>
        <p>Leslie Eaton</p>
      </block>
